
> On the outskirts of the thousand-year-old city lived a philosopher who
taught that the world was simple and that happiness was within the reach of
every man.

_The Courage to Be Disliked_ is a series of conversations between a
philosopher and a youth who feels downtrodden and unhappy. Despite the
philosopher's view that anyone can be happy, he preaches a philosophy of
maximum responsibility. Neither the world, your upbringing, nor your
environment are responsible for your unhappiness. The ideas are from the great
psychologist Alfred Adler.

**Trauma does not explain behavior.** The past nor the future exist.
There is only the now, and how we make sense of memories.

> No experience is in itself a cause of our success or failure. We do not
suffer from the shock of our experiences--the so-called trauma--but instead we
make out of them whatever suits our purposes. We are not determined by our
experiences, but the meaning we give them is self-determining.

For example, you may hold onto a grudge when a friend wrongs you. You'll
invent all these reasons why you dislike them. If you realize that your grudge
has no impact on them and only hurts yourself, it becomes easy to move on.
This would be impossible if indeed your frustration were caused by their
wrongdoing.

It's not that trauma doesn't have impact. The philosopher clarifies this
point:

> He [Adler] is not saying that the experience of a horrible calamity or abuse
during childhood or other such incidents have no influence on forming a
personality; their influences are strong. But the important thing is that
nothing is actually determined by those influences. We determine our own lives
according to the meaning we give to those past experiences. Your life is not
something that someone gives you, but something you choose yourself, and you
are the one who decides how you live.

**People lack the courage to change.**
It's much easier to say that you always wanted to be a writer—that you never
had the time—than to give it your best effort and face failure.

> Simply put, people have various complaints about things, but it's easier and
more secure to be just the way one is ... When we try to change our
lifestyles, we put our great courage to the test.


**Life can be simple and uncomplicated.**
In the communities where we participate, there are certain unavoidable
relationships. Adler calls the responsibilities we face in these
relationships, "life tasks". Much of the complication and antagonism we face
in these relationships stems from taking on another's life tasks.

> Whether the child studies or not. Whether he goes out and plays with his
friends or not. Essentially this is the child's task, not the parent's task
... In general, all interpersonal relationship troubles are caused by
intruding on other people's tasks, or having one's own tasks intruded on ...
If it's studying that is the issue, one tells the child that that is his task,
and one lets him know that one is ready to assist him whenever he has the urge
to study. But one must not intrude on the child's task.

