**The greatest unhappiness is not being able to like oneself.**

> For a human being, the greatest unhappiness is not being able to like
oneself. Adler came up with an extremely simple answer to address this
reality. Namely, that the feeling of "I am beneficial to the community" or "I
am of use to someone" is the only thing that can give one a true awareness
that one has worth.

Much of the book is dedicated to the problem of feeling worth. On one hand,
each person has this self, this soul, this most authentic self which points in
one direction. On the other hand there is this desire to be proud of oneself,
to feel valuable. Both are real desires that tug at one another.

In order to feel valuable, we compete with other people. We seek recognition.
We try to make every person like us.

> What should one do to not be disliked by anyone? There is only one answer:
It is to constantly gauge other people's feelings while swearing loyalty to
all of them ... If one is living in such a way as to satisfy other people's
expectations, and one is entrusting one's own life to others, that is a way of
living in which one is lying to oneself and continuing that lying to include
the people around one.

If we try to please everyone, we cannot possibly satisfy the desires of our
soul.

The second desire is to feel worth. Adler is very specific, when he states
that the feeling of contribution is the path towards feeling worth. This is
explained in the context of Adler's ideas on the ideal community, and makes
sense when paired with his belief that people are seeking a place to belong.

I'm not convinced. In my own life, my most clear desire is to be proud—to do
the right thing, to be honest, to be the best version of myself. There are
things I do, which make me feel proud that seem entirely self-serving, where
I'm not of use to anyone in particular.


